      },
      "lineNbr": 232,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "At the cost of some complexity here, you can concatenate all consecutive matrix_3x4 stages into a single matrix stage. (Basically, as long as fInvertStyle isn\u0027t InvertLightness, you only need one matrix_3x4 and the two clamps.)",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a4abc7af_e99814c7",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 232,
      "author": {
        "id": 6205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T20:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My only hesitation here is that\n\n(1) inverting lightness is the preferred choice so I don\u0027t want to increase\nthe complexity of the code to optimize a case that will be less common anyway\nand already inherently faster, and\n\n(2) it feels like collapsing matrices ought to be done by SkRasterPipeline\nas an optimization, rather than forcing every filter to do it. Wouldn\u0027t that be\na trivial one-pass optimization that we could add later? In theory we could\noptimize matrices of different sizes too. This could be a big win if earlier or\nlater stages in the pipeline also often include matrix calculations.",
      "parentUuid": "da0ec2f6_75ffbdd8",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "70177830_91c8fdbb",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 232,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T20:52:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "2 is something we could do at a couple different layers here, or just choose not to do.\n\nIn the past we have indeed done optimizations like this at lower levels (e.g. notice that the whole pipeline is really some sort of memset), but ultimately found the code easiest to maintain when these optimizations are applied at the highest level possible, when they actively know the optimization is possible rather than having to forget and re-detect it.\n\nNo other stage today uses matrix multiplications back to back... they concat them ahead of time and use one matrix_NxM stage.\n\nWhy don\u0027t we start with the code simple like this, then circle around to be fancy if we find a need?",
      "parentUuid": "a4abc7af_e99814c7",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e1362d1b_67f566ac",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 232,
      "author": {
        "id": 6205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T23:02:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sounds great.\n\nThe current change looks like a reasonable compromise between\nefficiency and simplicity. I\u0027d like to see how efficient it is in practice\nbefore worrying about optimizing it further.",
      "parentUuid": "70177830_91c8fdbb",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b6eb7b21_62525763",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 388,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We\u0027ve stopped injecting \\t and \\n in the shader code like this. It makes it harder to read, and we now have a pretty-printer that handles formatting whenever we need to see the final shader source code.\n\nAdditionally, I think much of this would be easier to read if it things were left vectorized (rather than broken into scalars):\n\ncodeAppendf(\"vec3 color \u003d %s;\", args.fInputColor);\n...\nif (grayscale) { codeAppendf(\"color \u003d dot(color, vec3(%f %f %f));\", SK_LUM_COEFF_R, SK_LUM_COEFF_G, SK_LUM_COEFF_B); }\n...\nif (invertBrightness) { codeAppend(\"color \u003d 1 - color;\"); }\n...\nif (invertLightness) { // This stays tricky, but you can keep referring to color.r, color.g, color.b }\n...\nif (contrast) { // All of the contrast code can be executed against \u0027color\u0027, no need for per-channel }\n...\ncodeAppend(\"color \u003d clamp(color, 0, 1);\")",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3112613f_bc5c4431",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 388,
      "author": {
        "id": 6205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T20:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh thank goodness, the \\t and \\n were really making it hard to read.\n\nI added a few spaces for indentation to make it easier to follow in the\nsource code, is that okay? I understand it will all be pretty-printed, but\notherwise it\u0027s hard to see where braces line up.\n\nI tried to do everything with vectors. I got it to work using vec4.\nIf there\u0027s a cleaner way to pull just r,g,b into a vec3 and then stuff it back\nat the end while preserving the alpha channel, please let me know.",
      "parentUuid": "b6eb7b21_62525763",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ae52af2a_aa7afb3f",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 403,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In addition to everything above, we would typically generate different shaders for the different features, rather than have the branches in the shader. So for this example:\n\nif (HighContrastInvertStyle \u003d\u003d invertStyle) {\n  codeAppend(\"color \u003d 1 - color;\");\n}\n\nFor that to work, GenKey needs to look like:\nGenKey(const GrProcessor\u0026 proc, const GrShaderCaps\u0026, GrProcessorKeyBuilder* b) {\n  const HighContrastFilterEffect \u0026hcfe \u003d proc.cast\u003cHighContrastFilterEffect\u003e();\n  b-\u003eadd32(hcfe.config().fInvertStyle);\n}\n\n... that rolls that parameter into the key we use to lookup the shader, so we cache the different variations separately. If you do this, you don\u0027t need the uniform for those parameters, and setData doesn\u0027t need to do anything either.",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2b4d95cd_650080e2",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 403,
      "author": {
        "id": 6205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T20:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh perfect - thanks for explaining more clearly what I need to do.\nI knew I needed something along those lines but couldn\u0027t figure out\nwhat I was doing wrong. I didn\u0027t realize how GenKey was related.\n\nI quantized the contrast parameter to use in the key, does that seem reasonable?\nThe valid range is -1.0 through 1.0.",
      "parentUuid": "ae52af2a_aa7afb3f",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9cabee4c_3c80dc6b",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 403,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T14:17:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027d leave the the contrast as a uniform, given that it\u0027s continuous. (If we ever have a UI slider to control it, for example, users could be causing us to generate and compile thousands of shaders...)",
      "parentUuid": "2b4d95cd_650080e2",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "935c043c_ff486741",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 765,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "While /2 is probably going to be compiled into *0.5f by a good compiler anyway, we tend to write things like this as *0.5f or *(1/2.0f) just to make it clear that this will not be a divide.\n\nFloat divides tend to be at least 3x more expensive than a multiply or add, and that\u0027s really the best case, so we take some care to avoid them.",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "61226618_122d6d8d",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 765,
      "author": {
        "id": 6205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T20:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Done",
      "parentUuid": "935c043c_ff486741",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d68533ad_90b32671",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 768,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There might be some way to make these more readable at a glance, as if they were a couple ?: or a little table of cases:\n\nauto s \u003d (max \u003d\u003d min).thenElse(0.0f, \n           (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(d / (2.0f - max - min),\n                               d / (max + min));\n\n\nGiven that all paths will actually execute, you might want to play around with reordering this math to avoid divides.\n\n (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(d / (2.0f - max - min), d / (max + min));\n\n~~~~\u003e\n\n d / (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(2.0f - max - min, max + min);",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
